# 🏗️ Architecture

> Structural decisions for the Agents Relay Orchestration module.


## Architecture

---

## A1 Relay Orchestrator Architecture
**Status:** draft
**Depends on:** G2

An LLM-based orchestrator would consume tokens for routing decisions, violating G3's token-efficiency mandate. It would also introduce non-determinism into flow execution. A deterministic state machine in Rust provides zero-token coordination, predictable routing, and compile-time safety.

```mermaid
graph TB
    subgraph "Orchestrator (Rust)"
        O[PipelineEngine]
        F[FlowSpec Parser]
        H[Handoff Manager]
        C[Checkpoint Manager]
        B[Budget Tracker]
    end
    subgraph "Agent Turn"
        A[AgentInstance]
        T[ToolRegistry Filter]
        AI[AI Provider]
    end
    subgraph "Specs (Ledger)"
        L[Jades / Ledger]
    end
    subgraph "Persistence"
        P[Checkpoint Store]
        R[Run Store]
    end

    O -->|parse| F
    O -->|generate| H
    O -->|save/load| C
    O -->|track| B
    O -->|spawn| A
    A -->|filtered| T
    A -->|chat| AI
    A -->|read/write| L
    C -->|serialize| P
    O -->|persist| R
```

| Approach | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|
| Deterministic Rust orchestrator | Zero token cost, predictable, fast, type-safe | Cannot adapt to novel flow patterns without code change |
| LLM-based orchestrator | Flexible, natural language flow definitions | Token cost per routing decision, non-deterministic, harder to test |
| Hybrid (LLM plans, Rust executes) | Flexibility + determinism | More complex, LLM still needed for plan generation |

- Positive: Flow execution is deterministic and unit-testable.
- Positive: No token spend on coordination.
- Negative: New flow patterns (e.g., conditional routing based on spec content) require code changes to `PipelineEngine`.
- Mitigation: FlowSpec supports `branch`, `loop`, and `on_fail` primitives that cover 95% of use cases.


---

## A2 Agent Instance Lifecycle
**Status:** draft
**Depends on:** G1, G2

Long-lived agent processes would accumulate context and state, defeating the token-efficiency goal. By spawning fresh instances per step, each agent starts with a clean, minimal context window. This also simplifies crash recovery — no need to restore agent memory, only the checkpoint.

```mermaid
stateDiagram-v2
    [*] --> Spawning: Orchestrator starts step
    Spawning --> Running: Soul + Specs + Handoff loaded
    Running --> ToolCall: Agent invokes tool
    ToolCall --> Running: Tool result appended
    Running --> HandoffComplete: Agent calls handoff tool
    Running --> BudgetExceeded: Token limit reached
    Running --> Error: Panic / API failure
    HandoffComplete --> [*]: Instance dropped, checkpoint saved
    BudgetExceeded --> [*]: Forced handoff, budget note added
    Error --> [*]: Run marked Failed, human notified
```

| Approach | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|
| Ephemeral per-step instances | Minimal context, easy recovery, cheap | Agent cannot learn across turns within a step |
| Long-lived instances with context window | Agent remembers earlier turns | Context grows, recovery harder, more tokens |
| Persistent agent processes with memory | Cross-run learning possible | Complex state management, not needed for relay |

- Positive: Maximum token efficiency.
- Positive: Crash recovery is trivial — just re-spawn from checkpoint.
- Negative: If an agent needs 5 turns to complete, each turn re-loads the same Soul + Specs. However, this is cheaper than maintaining a growing context.


---

## A3 Checkpoint & State Persistence
**Status:** draft
**Depends on:** G4

JSON provides human-readable, version-controllable checkpoints. Git auto-commits provide a robust file-level rollback mechanism that integrates with existing developer workflows. The Ledger is embedded (not referenced) to ensure self-contained checkpoints.

```mermaid
graph LR
    A[Handoff Triggered] --> B[Capture File Manifest]
    B --> C[Git Commit or Diff]
    C --> D[Serialize Ledger]
    D --> E[Write Handoff Document]
    E --> F[Write Checkpoint JSON]
    F --> G[Update Run Store]
```

| Approach | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|
| JSON + git | Human-readable, git-native rollback, simple | Large checkpoints for big projects |
| SQLite + binary blobs | Compact, queryable | Harder to inspect, git-unfriendly |
| Content-addressed store (IPFS-style) | Deduplication, immutable | Overkill for local orchestration |

- Positive: Checkpoints can be inspected with `cat` or `jq`.
- Positive: Rollback uses standard git commands.
- Negative: Large projects may produce multi-MB checkpoint files.
- Mitigation: File manifest stores hashes, not contents. Only changed files are diffed.

---

## A4 Boss-First Execution Architecture
**Status:** approved
**Depends on:** G6

The default workflow for AI assistants requires human approval at every step. This treats the human as a peer reviewer. AutoForge treats the human as a boss who delegates and expects results. GSD mode shifts the default from "ask for permission" to "ask for forgiveness" — the AI executes autonomously and only interrupts the boss when blocked.

```mermaid
graph LR
    A[Boss Request] --> B{Assistant classify}
    B -->|QUESTION| C[Answer & Stop]
    B -->|DIRECT| D[Coder]
    B -->|NEW_GOAL| E[Advisor]
    E -->|GSD| F{GoalGate}
    F -->|Auto| G[Architect]
    G --> H[Planner]
    H --> I[Coder]
    I --> J{Tests pass?}
    J -->|No| I
    J -->|Yes| K[Reviewer]
    K --> L[Documenter]
    L --> M[Report to Boss]
    F -->|Check mode| N[Human Review]
    N --> G
```

| Approach | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|
| GSD default, Check opt-in | Boss is productive; AI does the work | AI may build wrong thing confidently |
| Check default, GSD opt-in | Boss reviews every step | Boss is a bottleneck; loses async value |
| Hybrid (GSD with auto-drifts) | Balance of speed and safety | More complex routing logic |

- Positive: Boss gives one order, receives one report.
- Positive: Reviewer acts as internal QA, not an external gate.
- Negative: If Advisor writes bad Goals, everything downstream is wrong.
- Mitigation: GoalGate is the one required human gate in GSD mode. Advisor uses medium/strong model.


